@node "install" "Installation"

  @{b}Installation@{ub}

  Installing the program is very easy. Just use the provided installer. Many
  thanks  to  Marco  Negri for the basic installer script (still the old one
  was used and modified).

  In  the directory 'config' you ought to put all the configuration you want
  to use. See @{"configuration" LINK config}.

  NOTE: Since BAH version 3.3.1 the installaling script has changed a little
  bit. Since that version, the installing script is going to add Arexx files
  just  outside BAH drawer. If you select BED: (the provided default one) as
  the  installing  directory,  some  of  the  files  are  going  to be added
  automatically  into  BED  paths. These files are the Arexx scripts and the
  Insert  files,  that  will  be  put into subdirectories as they are in BAH 
  archive.
  
  If  for  some  reason  you want to install it by hand just copy the entire
  drawer  into  BED  directory  so to have a BED/bah drawer there. Then drag
  respectively  BAH Rexx and Support drawers on BED Rexx and Support ones so
  that   all   the   contained   files  are  installed  correctly  in  their
  subdirectories.

  If  a directory different from the BED: one is chosen for the installation
  then  it is likely that some functions are not going to work directly from
  the provided configuration files. You have to change the paths stated into
  them to match your own ones.

@endnode

@node "intro" "Introduction"

  @{b}Introduction @{ub}

  BED  Arexx Handler is a tool which must be used together with BlacksEditor
  (BED)  by  Marco  Negri  &  Paul Schifferer, a very good text editor which
  makes low memory needs and configuration options its major features.

  As  BED  has  a very complete AREXX interface through which the editor can
  do  everything  it  is  capable of and as it is completely configurable, I
  thought of a way to send AREXX commands in a easy way.

  BAH  opens  windows  which  contain buttons on BED's screen, through which
  the  user  can  easily  send  commands or macro. This makes BED similar to
  those   expensive   commercial  packages  where  some  operations  can  be
  performed  using  a  tool bar. BAH is different in the sense that the user
  can  @{"configure"  LINK config} it completely, from the number of buttons
  on a line to the number of lines in the window.

  BAH  is  auto  font sensitive and it uses BED's font menu. That means that
  if  you want to change BAH font you have simply to change BED's menu font.
  No  font  option  is  built  into  BAH  to  keep  the  program as small as
  possible.

  BAH  has  been  released as a CARDWARE program. That means you are morally
  obliged to send @{"me" LINK "author"} a postal card of your town if you like it (not so
  expensive, then).

@endnode

@node "news" "What's new"

  @{b}What's new in version 3.6.@{ub}

   New features of version 3.6 since version 3.4:
    - Changed a lot internally. Lots of small improvements also in speed. 
    
    - Fixed problem when trying to distribute left space on a line
      containing only SPACE or TEXT gadgets.
      
    - New LABEL keyword. This one works as the old TEXT, aligning the text
      in the available space, while TEXT has been removed.
      
    - Fixed error with the AREXX port not replying to the sender if the
      QUIT message was received. If the command was sent by BED this bug
      would not quit BED.
    
    - New AREXX commands and Arexx Macros examples.
    
    - AREXX commands are now really case insensitive. A stupid typo in the
      source code prevented this to work in the previous releases. Sorry.
    
    - The Project Manager has been removed. It was quite useless. I have to
      work on it more when I can (finally) get new BED versions.
    
    - Compiled with register optimiation enabled (smaller and faster code).
    
    - Lots of internal small changes and optimizations (they seems to never
      be enough 8) ).
    
    - Snapshot and Restore menu to save and restore the position of the
      window.
    
    - Initial configuration file can be set as tooltype.
    
    - Option to suppress warning messages coming from internal procedures
      and from AREXX port.
    
  New features of version 3.4 since version 3.3.1:
    - Window iconification.

  New features of version 3.3.1 since version 3.2:

    - The program now includes a @{"Project Manager" LINK "PMW"} that is going
    to be developed further in the future.

    - New Arexx commands for the Project Manager have been added.

    - Initial configuration file can be stated in the command line.

    - Better configuration parsing. Errors are reported in requesters and
      other bugs fixed (no more infinite loops for any error, program
      doesn't exit if a configuration error has been found).

  New features of version 3.0 since version 1.2 include:

    - Completely OOP coded, so it is much easier to modify and add
      features.

    - No more BGUI library needed! All the layout calculations done
      internally for faster and smaller code.

    - Low memory usage.

    - Single task handling multiple windows.

    - Pseudo frame support. Now buttons can be grouped into frames that can
      be aligned vertically or horizontally.

    - Multiple configuration can be loaded at once through the new LOADDOC
      command.

    - New RELOAD command that allow the configuration file to be reloaded
      after user modifications (no need to look for the config file through
      the file requester).

    - Through new TEXT keyword normal text can be added betwen buttons.

    - New SPACE and VSPACE (vertical space) added with a size parameter.

    - Excuting a copy of the program when another one is still running
      opens a file requester allowing the user to choose a new
      configuration file to be loaded. This has changed since version
      3.3.1. As the configuration file can be stated in the command line if
      no file is given nothing happens otherwise the config file is loaded.

    - New POSITION keyword allow to place the window everywhere desired on
      the screen at the opening of the window.

@endnode

@node "config" "Configuration"

  @{b}Configuration@{ub}

  BAH  always  wants  a initial configuration file for starting. This may be
  either  a  simple  configuration  or containing loading commands for other
  configurations.  If  no  configuration file is passed, both in the command
  line  or  as  tooltype  when  started frm WB, the default configuration is
  used. This configuration file is BED:BAH/config/main.cfg.

  Every  window has a configuration file. New windows can be opened with the
  OPEN menu command and selecting a configuration file from the requester.

  Let's  see how to create these configuration files. These are simple ASCII
  files  that  can be edited with any text editor (I suppose BED is what you
  are going to use, aren't you?)

                @{B}IMPORTANT!   IMPORTANT!   IMPORTANT!@{UB}
  
  As  I  have  eliminated the VSPACE keyword, whose features are now part of
  NEWLINE  keyword, some old configuration file may not work at all (a fatal
  error coul be reported). Fixing them is quite easy, just change the VSPACE
  keyword with NEWLINE and everything should work as before.
  I  have  also eliminated the TEXT keyword, now called LABEL. Labels can be
  left/center/right aligned.
  @{B}Sorry for these changes which should be the last ones.@{UB}

  Here are all the keywords recognized by BAH.

  POSITION    COLS      SPACE     LOADDOC

  TITLE       ROWS      BUTTON    ; (semicolon)

  NEWFRAME    NEWLINE   LABEL     

  Let's explain them in details.

  Keyword: @{b};@{ub}
  The  semicolon  indicates  that  the  line  is a comment and so it will be
  entirely skipped.

  Keyword: @{b}POSITION x y@{ub}
  POSITION  keyword  is followed by two parameters that indicate the x and y
  position respectively of the window on the screen. They can be anything in
  the  range  0-65534.  Moreover  y  can  be  set  as "BAR" (with quotes) to
  indicate  that  the  window must be positioned just under the screen title
  bar.

  Keyword: @{b}TITLE "text"@{ub}
  The  TITLE keyword is followed by a text surrounded by quotes that defines
  the window title.

  Keyword: @{b}NEWFRAME@{ub}
  No  parameters  for  this.  This means that a new group of lines has to be
  created.  At  least  one of this must be present in the config file before
  any line creation keyword.

  Keyword: @{b}COLS@{ub}
  Align frames horizontally.

  Keyword: @{b}ROWS@{ub}
  Align frames vertically.

  Keyword: @{b}NEWLINE "size"@{ub}
  It  means  that  a  new  line  has to be created in this point and it will
  belong  to the last created frame. Note that a line must be created before
  any  button  creation. Space determines how many empty pixels must be left
  from  the  previous line (sort of gap). It can be a number or a predefined
  keyword. See below for a detail report of allowed predefined attributes.

  Keyword: @{b}BUTTON "label" "command"@{ub}
  This  allow to define the button that has to be created. It is followed by
  two  strings surrounded by quotes that define repectively the label of the
  button and the Arexx command (or macro) that has to be sent to BED through
  its  Arexx  interface. The real size of the button cannot be defined as it
  will be eventually expanded to occupy the room left on the line.

  Keyword: @{b}LABEL "text" alignment@{ub}
  This  creates  a  label to be put in the window to identify some groups of
  buttons or lines. The text must be surrounded by quotes. Allowed alignment
  keywords are LEFT/CENTER/RIGHT an must not be surrounded by quotes.

  Keyword: @{b}SPACE "size"@{ub}
  This  creates  a blank space, used to divide groups of buttons on the same
  line. See below for allowed sizes. The number of pixels can also be stated
  directly (with or without quotes).

  Keyword: @{b}LOADDOC "path"@{ub}
  This  keyword allows for the loading of other windows that must be created
  together  to  this  config  file. The keyword can appear everywhere in the
  config  file  even  many times. The parameter QUIET can be added AFTER the
  name  of  the  configuration file to indicate that if a configuration with
  the  same name has already been loaded or the configuration file cannot be
  found  then  no  error  messages  will  be shown. Recursive calling inside
  configuration files are prevented.

  Allowed size keyword for SPACE and NEWLINE:
  - "VERY SMALL"
  - "SMALL"
  - "NORMAL"
  - "BIG"
  - "VERY BIG"
  - empty quotes ("") means 0

  WARNING:  all  keywords'  parameters  (but the alignment keywords) @{b}MUST@{Ub} be
  surrounded by quotes (single or double) and @{b}MUST@{ub} always be provided (empty
  quotes are fine).

  A direct number for specification of the SPACE and NEWLINE commands can be
  used.  The value is the number of pixels that have to be used. The numbers
  may be not surrounded by quotes.

  To  know  more  about keywords and their usage have a look at the included
  config files.

@endnode

