@node "commands" "Arexx Commands"

  @{b}BAH  Arexx Commands@{ub}

  Can  an  Arexx Handler not have an Arexx port? Sure it cannot! Even though
  not  documented  in the previous relese, BAH supports a QUIT command which
  closes all the related windows. The complete list of Arexx commands:
  
    - Quit
    - CloseDoc
    - LoadDoc
    - Iconify
    - Select
    - GetWinPos
    - SaveWinPos
    - RestoreWinPos
    - MoveWindow
    - Reload
  
  All commands are case insensitive.

  If you need any other command contact @{"me" LINK "author"}.


  @{B}How to use them.@{UB}
  
  All commands work in two ways: they act on the last panel selected through
  the  Select  command,  or  on the specified one following the command. All
  panels  are  selected  by  the  name  of  their window (case insensitive).
  Selecting a toolbar with the mouse does not make it the currently selected
  one;  only  through  the  use of Select a window is made target of all the
  future Arexx commands.
  
  So,  for  example,  you can use the 'Iconify' command alone to iconify the
  last  selected  toolbar, or use 'Iconify Misc' to act on the toolbar whose
  window  name  is  'Misc' (case insensitive, so it could be 'MISC', 'misc',
  'MiSc' and so on).
  
  @{B}Iconify@{UB} [name/ALL] [ON/OFF]
  Iconify a toolbar bringing it at its minimum size, that is the size of the
  tille  bar. A name may be passed as parameter. If the parameter is ALL all
  the  windows  will  affected  by the command. If ON is passed as a further
  parameter  the  winodw(s)  will  be  iconified, otherwise it(they) will be
  expanded  to  their  original  size.  If  neither  ON or OFF is passed the
  command will toggle between the normal and iconified status and viceversa.
  @{B}Note:  Due to the way commands are parsed, you cannot give a window one of
  these names (case insensitive): ALL, ON, OFF, TOGGLE.@{UB}
  
  @{B}LoadDoc@{UB} config [QUIET]
  Open  a new window with a new configuration. If the optional QUIET flag is
  set  no  warnings are returned if the configuration as been already opened
  or it cannot be found.
  
  @{B}Select@{UB} name
  Select a toolbar by the name of its window (case insensitive). 
  
  @{B}MoveWindow@{UB} [name] Xpos Ypos [REL]
  The  name  of  the  toolbar  is  optional. Xpos and Ypos are the coords in
  pixels where to place the upper left corner of the window. Ypos can be the
  special  keyword  "BAR"  to  specify that the window must be placed always
  under the title bar of the screen whatever is the size of the title bar.
  REL  is an optional keyword stating, if present, that the movement must be
  relative to the current window position instead of being absolute (default
  behaviour if REL if not stated).
  I.e. MOVEWINDOW 200 100   or   Movewindow Doc 20 10 REL
  
  @{B}GetWinPos@{UB} [name]
  Return the position and size of the current or selected toolbar.
  
  @{B}RestoreWinPos@{UB} [name]
  Move  the  window  to  the original place where it was when the window has
  been opened or at the last saved position.
  
  @{B}SaveWinPos@{UB} [name]
  Save  the current position of the toolbar permanently in the configuration
  file.
  
  @{B}Reload@{UB} [name]
  Reload the configuration completely.
  
@endnode

@node "use" "How to use it"

  @{b}How to use it (v3.6)@{ub}

  It  can't  be  so easy... execute it as CLI program or double click on its
  icon.  As a CLI command it accepts a complete filename (that is path+name)
  as  its  initial  configuration  file.  When  launched  from the icon, the
  filename  can  be set as the CONFIG tooltype. If no configuration is given
  the default one is used.
  
  See @{"configuration" LINK "configuration"} section for more info about this.

  Every toolbar window has four menus with this layout: 

    Projects      Tools               Window            Settings
      Open          Iconify             Snap              Quiet
      Reload        Iconify All ON      Restore           Force
      About         Iconify All OFF     Save Position   
      Close         
      Quit

  @{U}@{B}Projects Menu:@{UB}@{UU}

  @{B}Open:@{UB} opens a requester to let you choose a config file to load.
    A new window (or set of windows) with the new configuration will then be
    opened.

  @{B}Reload:@{UB} it reloads the current configuration in the current window.
    Useful if you keep on modifing the config files and want to see the
    results immediately.

  @{B}About:@{UB} need any comment?

  @{B}Close:@{UB} close the current window leaving the other ones untouched.
    Note that if the closed window is the last one the program will
    automatically quit (so the Arexx port will be removed).

  @{B}Quit:@{UB} close all BAH windows and quit the program.

  @{U}@{B}Tools Menu:@{UB}@{UU}
    
  @{B}Iconify:@{UB} iconify the current window
  
  @{B}Iconify All ON:@{UB} iconify all the windows
  
  @{B}Iconify All OFF:@{UB} reopen all the iconified windows

  @{U}@{B}Window Menu:@{UB}@{UU}
  
  @{B}Snap:@{UB} show the current position of the window.
  
  @{B}Restore:@{UB} move the window to its original position (the one stored
    in the configuration file).

  @{B}Save Position@{UB} store the current coords of the window in the
    configuration file.

  @{U}@{B}Settings Menu:@{UB}@{UU}
  
  @{B}Quiet:@{UB} avoid that error messages are displayed when operating with
    menus (like, for example, trying to load a non existent configuration
    file). Errors coming from AREXX commands are displayed.
  
  @{B}Force:@{UB} avoid all error messages that come from menu and AREXX
    commands.
  
@endnode

@node "arexx" "Arexx Scripts"

  @{b}Supplied Arexx scripts@{ub}

  Together  with  BAH  I  have  included  some Arexx scripts I have done and
  enjoyed.  They are quite simple, but may be very useful to someone of you.

  I  am  not  very  good  at  Arexx,  and so I'm sure they can be written in
  different ways with better results, but they work flawlessly for me.

  The included Arexx script are:

  BAH/

    - Quit            Quit BAH.
    - Load            Load a new configuration file.
    - Iconify         Iconify BAH windows.
    - Reload          Reload onfiguration of current toolbar.
    - Restore         Restore the window poition of current toolbar.
    - Select          Select a new toolbar as current one.
    - MoveWindow      Move window examples.
    - GetWinPos       Get the current window position and size.

  E/

    - EBuild          Uses Autobuild to compile the modules.
    - ECompile        Compile the selected document (NOCACHE).
    - ECompileCache   Compile the selected document with CACHE enabled.
    - EcompileDbg     Compile the selected document with debugging code.
    - EDBG            Run the debugger on the selecteed document. Note that
                      the module must be compiled with debug code.
    - EditAutoBuild   Edit the .autobuild file needed for EBuild.
    - EditFile        Edit one of the predefined files: hystory,
                      development and description, useful for mantaining
                      complex projects.

  HTML/

    - AddEffect       Script used by the HTML toolbar

  Altri:

    - ReloadDoc       Reload the current file (Restore the last saved
                      version).
    - InsertMyVersion Slightly modified original InsertVersion.
    - ReplaceDate     If the cursor is on a date string this will update it
                      with the current one.
    - SelectDocGUI    Modified original SelectDoc now uses a number
                      requester and disappears automatically.
    - SplitIndex      splits the Aminet Index into smaller files so being
                      able to handle it much easily. Note that you need to
                      load the index completely in order to split it.

  They  are  almost  all called by some button of the provided configuration
  files.

  Furthermore there are some simple files that are used with some buttons of
  the  provided  configurations.  They  can be easily modified to match your
  tastes. These are:

  Support/Insert/

    - Box.ins
    - Edges.ins
    - Edges2.ins
    - Line.ins

  Note: The files are installed in their positions where they will be looked
  for.  If  you  change their path you will need to modify BAH configuration
  files or some Arexx scripts, but this should not be a big problem.

  All the files listed here are freerly distributable and may be modified at
  will, but please do not distribute BAH without the original ones. 
  
  If  you have a good configuration file or an Arexx script that you want to
  see added to BAH distribution package then just send them to @{"me" LINK "author"}

@endnode

@node "A1200" "A1200 configuration"

  This is my A1200 configuration:

  Brand old A1200 (Commodore production) fitted in a custom big and heavy
  black desktop case that hosts, other than the mainboard:

  - a Blizzard 1240 T/ERC
  - 16 Mbyte of Fast RAM
  - 1.6 Gbyte Western Digital HD
  - CD 8x
  - The power is dragged by the internal 200W power supply (no more
    problems with those bricks limited to 3A or 5A).

  - The keyboard, hacked on the motherboard, is a A1200 keyboard fitted into
    an A3000 keyboard chassis. Once there was a glorious A1000 keyboard
    before it passed to a better life (so the say) after more than 13 years
    of work. 
  - Well, a bit of soldering and the A1000 keyboard is back again (I hope
    for other 14 years of faithful service!).

  On top of it there's a NEC Multisync II monitor (perfect for AGA chipset).
  All has been working in this configuration for almost three years now.

  On its side there are two Epson printers, a 9 pin LX 400 and a Stylus
  800+ (which is now probably dead 8( ).

@endnode

@node "PMW" "Project Manager WIndow"

  This part has been removed due to some technical problems.
  
  I will return on this as soon BED will be updated (if ever).


@endnode

@node "Obsolete" "Obsolete"

  You should not be reading this...

  @{b}The Project Manager Window@{ub}

  This is a new feature introduced with version 3.3.0.

  The window appears on the extreme right of the screen (its position is
  not user definable yet), and features 5 buttons:

    - List: Performs a scan of the currently available documents and
      displays them in the window. This is done automatically when the
      window is opened and must be performed manually every time new
      documents are opened/closed to keep the list up to date.
    
      Documents can be selected directly with the mouse on the list that can
      be scrolled to show all the available documents.

    - Iconify: Iconify the selected document
    
    - Display: Restore the current document if it is iconified.

    - Hide: Hide the document window removing it from the screen, The
      document is still in memory, though. Useful to make some romm on the
      screen if many documents are opened.

    - Show: Redisplay the hidden document.

  As there are some problems with BAH ControlWindow Arexx coammand, the Hide
  and Show buttons have been disabled. This is to avoid to incur in a series
  of  nastuy  enforcer-hits that are not dangerous but are not nice to have.
  As  soon  as  the  ControlWIndow  command,  that is used for the temporary
  removal of a document window from the screen is fixeed, those buttons will
  be made workable again.

  As  project  managing is going to be further developed new commands can be
  added (probably even on a user definable configuration file).

  Selecting  again  the  same  highlighted  document equals to executing the
  display  command,  and  the  selected  document  will  be de-iconified and
  brought to the front automatically.

  The  Project  Manager window has also a menu similar to that of the button
  windows:
   
    Projects      Tools
     Open          BAH
     About
     Close
     CloseAll
     Quit

  @{B}Open:@{UB} Not yet functional. It will be used to load a project file (in ASCII
    format)  where  lots of information about the documents are stored, very
    similar  to  BED  desktop  files,  but containing many other useful data
    (dependancy,  BED definition file to be used... and probably much more).
    Different  windows  may  keep  different  and  independant parts of a
    more complex project.

   @{B}About:@{UB} Same as in BAH button windows.
   
   @{B}Close:@{UB} Close the current Project Manager window

   @{B}CloseAll:@{UB}  Close all Project Manager windows but leave BAH button windows
     opened if present, otherwise quit.

   @{B}Quit:@{UB}  Close everything, both Project Manager windows and button windows.

  The  other  option  in  the  Tools  Menu  is  @{B}BAH@{UB}  which  loads  the  main 
  configuration  file if all button windows have been closed or it opens the
  file  requester for configuration loading if at least one button window is
  still open.

@endnode

@node "problems" "Problems"

  @{B}Problems@{UB}

  No problems are known. It is possible that the program will behave in a
  strange and unexpected way if the configuration files contain errors.

@endnode


